[SetUp "1"]

1. b4
{ The idea of this bizarre-looking move is to stop Black's attack on the queenside a little and keep the c-file and the 4th rank closed.  The immediate   26.h5  doesn't work  cxb3  27.Qe4  b2  -+  and Black wins too much material with his b-pawn.  The normal   26.bxc4  gives White only a small edge  Qc5  27.Ra2  Nxc4  28.h5  Rb2  29.Qc3  Here we see the difference between b4 and bxc4. White is unable to keep his queen on the b1-h7 diagonal, since   29.Qe4 ?  Nd2  -+  is just winning for Black  29...Rxa2  30.Nxa2  g5  31.Nd3  Qb6  += }
1... Rxb4 2. h5 Rb2 3. Qe4
{ and Black's position falls apart quickly. He either loses his g6-pawn or gets into a crushing attack after   28...g5  29.Qxf5  gxf4  30.Be4  +- }
*

