[White "Brainteasers"]
[Black "Cmilyte, Viktorija(2220) vs. Aksiuczyc, Monika(2180)"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "6k1/2q1ppbp/3p1np1/1r1P4/2pBP3/5PPB/rPQ4P/1R1R2K1 b - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

Nxd5 2. exd5 { 21.Bxg7  Ne3  22.Qd2  Nxd1  -+ } 2... Bxd4+ 3. Rxd4 Qb6 4. Qxc4
{ 23.Qf2  is also hopeless.  Rbxb2  24.Rxb2  Rxb2  25.Qe3  Rb1+  26.Bf1   26.Kf2  Rb3  Now that f2 is blocked for the queen, this simply wins the rook on d4.  27.Qd2  Rd3  -+  26...c3  27.Qxc3  Rd1  -+ }
4... Rbxb2
{ Not   23...Raxb2 ??  24.Rxb2  Rxb2  25.Qc8+  Kg7  26.Qc3  +-  and Black has nothing. }
5. Rxb2 { 24.Rbd1  Rd2  -+ } 5... Qxb2
{ Black has a crushing attack along the second rank. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Brainteasers"]
[Black "Knapp, Michael(1964) vs. Kuesgen, Dirk"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r1r3k1/q3ppbp/b2p2p1/2pPn3/6n1/1PB2NP1/P1QNPPBP/3RR1K1 b - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

1... Nxf2 { Starting with   19...c4  doesn't work because of  20.Bd4  += } 2.
Bxe5
{ 20.Kxf2  ends in a smothered mate  Ng4+  21.Kg1   21.Kf1  Ne3+  -+  21...c4+  22.Kh1  Nf2+  -+ }
2... c4
{ 20...Nxd1  21.Bxg7  Ne3  22.Qb2  f6  23.Bh6 =  is anything but clear } 3.
Bxg7
{ 21.e3  just leaves Black with extra material  Nxd1  22.Bxg7   22.Bd4  Bxd4  23.exd4  cxb3  24.Qxd1  bxa2  -+  22...Nxe3  -+ }
3... Nh3+ 4. Kh1 Qg1+ 5. Nxg1 Nf2# *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Brainteasers"]
[Black "Gligoric, Svetozar(2454) vs. Nyback, Tomi(2497)"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "2r3k1/4ppbp/q2p2p1/3Pn2n/P1r1P3/1QN2P1P/4N1PK/1R1RB3 b - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ Can you find Black's correct way of attack in this complicated position ? }
1... Rxc3
{ This is the most precise, since   21...Nxf3+  allows White to stop the attack with  22.gxf3  Rxc3  23.Qb5  ∓  Black is obviously still for choice, but White has good fighting chances here. }
2. Nxc3 Nxf3+
{ Again this is the precise move order   22...Qf1  23.Ne2 !  Qxe2  24.Rd2  Qf1  25.Rf2  ∓  is very unclear }
3. gxf3 Qf1 { 23...Bxc3 ?  is again refuted by  24.Qb5 ! = } 4. Bg3
{ The only way to stop Be5+ } 4... Qxf3 5. Nb5 Qe2+
{ 25...Rc3  is another elegant way to win  26.Nxc3  Qxg3+  -+  and Black's attack is crushing }
6. Kg1 Rc2 7. Qxc2 Qxc2
{ White's weak king coupled with his weak pawns, gives Black a winning edge, even though White seemingly has enough material for the queen }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Brainteasers"]
[Black "Cherniaev, Alexander1(2265) vs. Kirillov, Igor(2293)"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "1r3rk1/1q2ppb1/b2p2p1/P1pPn1Np/2P4P/5NPB/2QBPP2/4R1K1 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ When Black has loosened his g6-pawn by moving the h7-pawn, tactics on the light squares are very common. Do you see how White can break through here ? }
1. Nxe5 { First remove the second to last defender } 1... Bxe5 2. Be6
{ Then the last one   22.Ne6 ?  is not forcing enough, note that White already invested an exchange into his attack. Black can simply play  Qb2  23.Qxb2  Rxb2  24.Nxf8  Kxf8  ∓  and will get back at least his pawn and have an excellent position }
2... Kg7 { 22...fxe6  doesn't work of course  23.Qxg6+  Bg7  24.Qh7# } 3. Nxf7
{ 23.Bxf7 ?  also looks promising, but Black can hold on to g6 here  Rxf7  24.Ne6+  Kh7  25.Ng5+ =  There is no way to make progress }
3... Rxf7 4. Bh6+
{ The final touch. The dark squared bishop is sacrificed to finally break though on the light squares }
4... Kxh6 5. Bxf7 { Finally g6 falls and with it the Black king. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Brainteasers"]
[Black "Hesham, Abdelrahman(2405) vs. Mehmeti, Dritan(2391)"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "6k1/4pp1p/1nNp2p1/2qP4/P3r3/5RP1/1Q3PKP/8 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

1. Rxf7
{ Surprisingly Black just gets mated now, but White has to find some amazing ideas how to coordinate knight and queen. }
1... Kxf7 2. Qh8 { Threatening Nd8# } 2... e6
{ After   31...g5  32.Nd8+  Kg6  33.Qg8+  Kf6  34.Qf7+  Ke5  it looks like Black's king can escape, but  35.Nc6+ !  wins }
3. Qxh7+ { 32.Nd8+  is only a repetition after  Ke7 } 3... Kf8
{ 32...Kf6  also leads to mate  33.Qe7+ !  Kf5  34.Qf7+  Kg5  35.Ne7  +-  followed by Qxg6 }
4. Nd8
{ 33.Qe7+  which was played in the game only leads to perpetual check.  Kg8  34.Qe8+  Kg7  and there is no way for queen and knight to coordinate effectively }
4... Ke8 5. Qg8+
{ 34.Nxe6  is only good for a draw  Rxe6  35.Qg8+   35.dxe6  Qd5+  36.Kg1  Qxe6  37.a5  Qe1+  38.Kg2  Qe4+ =  35...Ke7  36.Qxe6+  Kd8  37.Qg8+  Kc7  38.Qf7+  Nd7  39.h4 = }
5... Kd7
{ 34...Ke7  This is the difference to the immediate 34. Nxe6. This move now loses quickly.  35.Nc6+ !  Kf6  36.Qf8+  Kg5  37.f4+  Kh5  38.Qh8+  Kg4  39.Qh3# }
6. Nxe6 Qxd5 { 35...Qc8  36.Qf7# } 7. Qf7+ Kc6 8. Qc7#
{ Who would have thought that the a4-pawn plays a crucial role in White's mating attack... }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Brainteasers"]
[Black "Firt, Stanislav(2315) vs. Helis, Tadeusz(2288)"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "rr3k2/4pn2/3p1pQ1/qbpP4/5P2/2P3PB/P3P2P/1R1R2K1 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

1. Rxb5 { Without this move Black could always defend with Be8 } 1... Qxb5 2.
Be6 Qe8 { So far so good, but What is White's idea here ? } 3. h4
{ This is it. The h-pawn simply marches down the board. } 3... Rxa2 4. h5 Rxe2
5. h6
{ and arrives right on time. Black gets mated before he can give a perpetual with both rooks along the 2nd rank. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Brainteasers"]
[Black "Malinin, Vasily Borisovich vs. Savinov, Viktor"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "1r1qr1k1/3nppb1/b2p2p1/2pn4/8/2N1BNPB/PPQ1PP2/R3K2R w KQ - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

1. Be6
{ This wins in an amazing fashion.   14.Qxg6  was the even more amazing game continuation. And even though after  fxg6  15.Be6+  Kf8  16.Nxd5  Rxb2  17.Ng5  White didn't have too much of an attack for the queen, he managed to win }
1... fxe6 2. Bh6
{ Fantastic. The idea of Be6 wasn't to win on the light, but on the dark, squares.   15.Qxg6  is less than nothing  (Nf8 -+) }
2... Nf8 { 15...Rxb2  16.Qxg6  +-  is mate } 3. Bxg7 Kxg7 4. Qd2
{ Qh6+ will come with devastating effect. Note how nearly all Black pieces are cut off from the kingside.   17.Qc1  is the same }
4... Nxc3 { 17...Rb4  18.Qh6+  Kf6  19.e4  +- } 5. Qh6+ Kf7
{ 18...Kf6  19.Qf4+  transposes } 6. Qf4+
{ 19.Ng5+  wins as well after  Kf6  20.Qh8+  Kf5  21.bxc3  +-  Black's king on f5 can't survive for long }
6... Kg7 7. Ng5 { and mate ! } *

